A PALLET WITH TEN 50 LB BAGS WAS LOADED INTO THE LEFT NOSE OF THE TRAILER AND NO DUNNAGED WAS USED TO PROTECT THE EXPOSED BAGS ON THE TOP LAYER. ANOTHER PIECE OF FREIGHT WAS NOT SECURE AND FELL ONTO THE TOP OF THE PALLET RIPPING ONE BAG OPEN DURING TRANSIT.  CONTENTS OF THE BAGS COVERED THE TOP OF THE PALLET AS WELL AS THE BIKE RACK WHICH FELL ON THE PALLET CAUSING THE RIP TO OCCUR.

UPON ARRIVAL AT THE TERMINAL TWO PAILS WERE DISCOVERED CRUSHED.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP USING A SPILL PAD AND PACKED INTO A PLASTIC BAG.  THE DAMAGED CONTAINERS WERE OVERPACKED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND WILL BE RETURNED TO THE ATLANTA FACILITY.  THEY WILL BE PLACED IN OS & D TO AWAIT DISPOSITION.

WHILE ENROUTE TO THE CUSTOMER, THE PRESSURE STARTED INCREASING INSIDE THE CARGO TANK.  THE DRIVER WOKE HIS PARTNER, WHO WAS IN THE SLEEPER CAB.  THEY PULLED OFF THE ROAD,  AND THE SAFETY FUNCTIONED.  THEY SWITCHED THE VALVE, TRANSFERRING THE CARGO TANK TO THE SECOND SAFETY.  ABOUT 150 LBS. OF PRODUCT WAS LOST.  THE DELIVERY WAS THEN CONTINUED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

column168: A 50 POUND PLASTIC BUCKET OF SWIMMING POOL CHEMICAL, "CALCIUM HYPOCHLORITE" WAS SHIPPED INSIDE A FIBREBOARD BOX.  THE DELIVERY DRIVER IN GREAT FALLS, MT REPORTED THE PACKAGE HAD OVERTURNED ON HIS VEHICLE AND THE SMELL WAS CAUSING HIM TO COUGH.  WE HAD HIM STOP THE VEHICLE, GET OUT AND CALL FOR A SPILL CLEAN-UP SPECIALIST FROM HIS STATION.  THE VEHICLE WAS CLEANED AND A SECOND DRIVER TOOK OVER THE ROUTE. column168: AT 1715 HOURS TRAIN F77501 WITH THREE ENGINES AND SEVENTY-SIX CARS (52 LOADS & 24 EMPTIES) HAD AN UNDESIRED BRAKE APPLICATION NEAR THE TOWN OF POLKTON, NC (MILE POST SF287.6 AND SF 286.6).  INVESTIGATION FOUND NINE (9) CARS DERAILED BEGINNING WITH THE 36TH HEAD CAR.  TANK CAR PROX16387 (LOAD- SULFURIC ACID) WAS FOUND WITH THE "A" END ON THE GROUND, "B" END STILL UP ON THE TRUCKS - HOWEVER OFF THE CENTER PIN, AND SIGHTLY LEANING.  THE ANSON COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND INITIALLY ISSUED A 0.5-MILE EVACUATION AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE.  A TOTAL OF 18 PEOPLE WERE EVACUATED FROM THE ROCKING HOUSE DAY CARE AND THE ANSON COUNTY CHILD DEVELOPMENT CENTER.  UPON ARRIVAL OF CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM THE INTEGRITY OF TANK CAR WAS INSPECTED, INFORMATION WAS RELAYED TO THE FIRST RESPONDERS, AND THE EVACUATION WAS LIFTED AT 2000 HOURS.  NO RELEASE OF PRODUCT OCCURRED AS A RESULT OF THIS DERAILMENT.

CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INSPECT THE CAR.  THE CONTRACTOR FOUND NO LEAKAGE ON UTLX950682. THE PLUG WAS REMOVED AND CLEANED.  THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE THROUGH THE CLOSED VALVE.  THE PLUG WAS INSTALLED WRENCH TIGHT.  THE CONTRACTOR LEAK CHECKED ALL THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS AND FOUND NO LEAKAGE.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED.  THE SHIPPER, PCS SALES, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC AND WAS ADVISED OF THE DEFICIENCIES FOUND.

column168: ON JULY 7, 2003, PERSONNEL IN THE CSX RAIL YARD IN DECATUR, AL OBSERVED ACFX 79836, A LOADED TANK CAR OF CRUDE SULPHATE TURPENTINE, LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CONTAINMENT MATERIALS PLACED UNDER THE LEAK.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE.  UPON ARRIVAL, THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THE CAR LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET GASKET.  CONTRACTOR PERSONNEL PLUGGED THE LEAK AND SECURED TRUCKS FOR PRODUCT TRANSFER.  LOCAL AUTHORITIES RESPONDED AND STOOD BY DURING TRANSFER OPERATIONS.  THE CONTENTS OF THE CAR WERE TRANSFERRED INTO TRUCKS AND AREA CLEANUP WAS CONDUCTED.  THE CONSIGNEE DISPATCHED A MOBILE CAR REPAIR CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR THE GASKET.

WHILE THE DRIVER WAS EN ROUTE TO THE CONSIGNEE THE DRIER HAD TO HIT HIS BRAKES HARD.  ANOTHER VEHICLE PASSED HIM AND THEN STOPPED IN FRONT OF HIM FOR NO REASON.  THE DRIVER HIT HIS BREAKS, IN ORDER TO KEEP FROM HAVING AN ACCIDENT.  THE MATERIAL IN THE BIN HAD TURNED TO LIQUID SLUDGE, AS THE DRIVER HIT HIS BREAKS THE MATERIAL CAME OUT OF THE BIN AT THE FRONT BETWEEN THE BIN AND THE LID.  THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS THAT SPILLED OUT HOWEVER MOST ALL OF THE MATERIAL THAT SPILLED OUT ENDED UP ON THE BACK OF THE TRUCK.  A CREW WAS SENT OUT TO CLEAN UP THE SOILED MATERIAL PRIOR TO THE TRUCK CONTINUING.  ONCE THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND THE LOAD WAS READY TO GO THE DRIVER CONTINUED ON HIS WAY TO THE CONSIGNEE WITH NO FURTHER INCIDENTS.  ALL OF THE MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP IN ACCORDANCE WITH ALL APPLICABLE FEDERAL REGULATION.

RCRX 1373, LOAD HYDROCHLORIC ACID, WAS FOUND LEAKING VAPORS FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR WHILE IT WAS BEING SWITCHED IN  CSX TRANSPORTATION'S GENTILLY YARD IN NEW ORLEANS, LA.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THE CAR IS EQUIPPED WITH A PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE.  AN ESTIMATED 1/2-PINT OF PRODUCT WAS FOUND AROUND THE BASE OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE. THE VALVE WAS IN THE CLOSED POSITION AND THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE AT THE TIME OF INVESTIGATION.  ALL THE MANWAY BOLTS AND OTHER FITTINGS ON THE CAR WERE TIGHT AND THERE WAS NO SIGN OF LEAKAGE NOTED FROM ANY OTHER AREA ON THE CAR IT APPEARS THAT THE LIQUID RELEASE FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE WAS POSSIBLY CAUSED BY AN IMPACT WITH ANOTHER RAIL CAR THAT COULD HAVE CAUSED THE VALVE TO OPEN AND THEN RESEAT.

ON JULY 9, 2003, A CSX SWITCHING CREW IN HENDERSON, KY, REPORTED THAT TWO TANK CARS DERAILED NEAR US HIGHWAY 60.  THERE WAS NO PRODUCT LEAKAGE.  THE SHIPPERS, CONSIGNEES, LOCAL AUTHORITIES AND RERAILING CONTRACTORS WERE NOTIFIED.  LOCAL EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT PERSONNEL ORDERED THE EVACUATION OF APPROXIMATELY 200 PERSON FROM 12 HOMES AND 5 BUSINESSES IN THE AREA.  US HIGHWAY 60 WAS CLOSED DURING THE RERAILING PROCESS.  THE CARS WERE RERAILED WITHOUT INCIDENT AND THE EVACUATION WAS LIFTED AT 09:15 ON JULY 10, 2003. ALSO INVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT WAS UTLX 66055, A LOADED TANK CAR OF POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE.

WHILE FREIGHT WAS BEING LOADED BEHIND THIS SHIPMENT FORKBLADE PUNCTURED ONE PLASTIC PAIL BECAUSE OF INATTION OF FORKLIFT DRIVER AND BECAUSE NO DUNNAGE WAS USED BETWEEN OR AROUND THE SHIPMENT.  SHIPPER EMERGENCY NUMBER WAS CALLED FOR MSDS FOR REPORT.  AFTER CLEAN UP FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS SPOKEN TO ABOUT FUTURE PREVENTATIVE MEASURES TO BE TAKEN SO THIS TYPE OF SPILL CAN BE PREVENTED...

(SATCO).  A CREWMEMBER WAS SPLASHED WITH ACID.  HE REMOVED HIS SHIRT AND WASHED OFF. HE WAS NOT INJURED.  THE CAR WAS INCORRECTLY BILLED TO SATCO.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE PROBLEM. UPON INSPECTION WE FOUND ONE OF THE DRUMS HAD A PUNCTURE IN THE LOWER SEAM OF THE DRUM.  IT WAS LEAKING SLIGHTY OUT OF IT WITH MOVEMENT OF THE FREIGHT.  THE SAFETY DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED. WE PUT SOME ABSORBENT ON THE TRAILER FLOOR TO ABSORB ABOUT.25 OUNCES.  THEN PROCEEDED TO PLACE THE DRUM IN AN OVERPACK THAT HOLDS A 55 GALLON DRUM.
BOX WAS LOADED AND CRUSHED BETWEEN 2 PALLETS.  INCIDENT REPORT IS PENDING UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER FAILED TO MAINTAIN LANE OF TRAFFIC WHILE TURNING FROM COUNTY ROAD TO O RAMP OF INTERSTATE HIGHWAY.  TRACTOR, SEMI TRAILER AND PUP TRAILER OVERTURNED.  THE SEMI-TRAILER REAR HEAD WAS PUNCTURED BY THE PUP TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY 75 BARRELS OF CRUDE OIL WAS RELEASED FROM THE PUP TRAILER.  A DIKE WAS CONSTRUCTED TO STOP THE SPREAD OF RELEASED CRUDE OIL. APPROXIMATELY 50 BARRELS OF CRUDE OIL WAS RECOVERED USING A VAC TRUCK.  A BURN PERMIT WAS OBTAINED FROM THE WYOMING D.E.Q. AND THE REMAINING CRUDE OIL WAS BURNED FROM THE SOIL.  APPROXIMATELY 25 YARDS OF SOIL WILL BE REMOVED FROM THE LOCATION FOR TREATMENT.  THE REMAINING AFFECTED AREA WILL BE FARMED IN PLACE, AS APPROVED BY THE LAND OWNER AND THE WYOMING D.E.Q.

column168: WHILE OUR DRIVER WAS UNLOADING HIS TANKER TRAILER, A HOSE BLEW AND PRODUCT LEAKED OUT ONTO THE GROUND.  THE PUMP WAS SHUT DOWN AND THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED & CLEANED UP.

column168: WHILE LOADING ONE DRUM WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE DRUM HAD A PINHOLE IN THE BOTTOM.  THE MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP USING A SPILL PAD AND PACKED INTO A PLASTIC BAG.  THE DAMAGED CONTAINER WAS OVERPACKED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND PLACED IN OS & D TO AWAIT DISPOSITION.

ONE DRUM WAS DISCOVERED DENTED AND LEAKING.  THE DRUM WAS IN THE PROCESS OF BEING UNLOADED WHEN THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP USING A CLAY ABSORBENT.  THE DAMAGED CONTAINER WAS OVERPACKED AND PLACED IN OS & D.

PLMX 32720 WAS NOTED BY CARRIER PERSONNEL WITH PRODUCT ODOR IN AREA OF CAR. CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  CONSIGNEE REPRESENTATIVES, HEPACO INC, RESPONDED AND REPLACED THE DEFECTIVE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE "O" RING STOPPING THE RELEASE.  CAR TO BE SHOPPED FOR FURTHER INSPECTION AND REPAIRS.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING TWO-HUNDRED SEVENTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC TOTE WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALF-WAY MARK OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY TWO PINTS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED TO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE BUNG.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND AMPHOMAG.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE LOOSE BUNG ON THE TWO-HUNDRED SEVENTY-FIVE GALLON TOTE WAS TIGHTENED AND THE TOTE WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECIEVED.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE MOVING FREIGHT INSIDE THE TRAILER, FOUR LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUMS WERE DISCOVERED IN THE LAST QUARTER OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY TWENTY OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO LOOSE CAPS ON THE TOPS OF THE DRUMS.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING A RESPIRATOR MASK, TYVEK SUIT, GOGGLES, GLOVES, AMPHOMAG, AND ABSORBENT PADS.  THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, TWENTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE LOOSE CAPS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE DRUMS WILL BE FORWARDED ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURE WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING AT THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY IN MARTINSBURG, WEST VIRGINIA, ONE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUM WAS DISCOVERED INSIDE THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE DRUM FALLING OVER IN TRANSIT, CAUSING A CHEMICAL REACTION, WHICH RESULTED IN FREE PRODUCT RELEASING FROM THE PRESSURE-RELIEF VALVE ON THE DRUM.  THE HAZMAT TEAM FROM ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. TERMINAL IN HAGERSTOWN, MARYLAND RESPONDED TO THE FACILITY TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, AMPHOMAG, AND ABSORBENT TOWELS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. TERMINAL IN HAGERSTOWN, MARYLAND, WHERE IT WILL BE HELD FOR DISPOSITION.  THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT WAS ACCEPTED BY THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: ON JULY 10, 2003 TRACOR TRAILER COMBINATION 342529 AND 2316 OVERTURNED ON I-35 SOUTHBOUND 5 MILES SOUTH OF HILLSBORO, TEXAS. IMMEDIATE FIRE STARTED AND ALL GASOLINE WAS BURNT ALONG WITH TRACTOR TRAILER. CLEANUP AND HAZMAT TEAM PRESSURE WASHED THE FREEWAYS BOTH SIDES AND BUILT COFFER DAMNS TO CONTAIN THE CONTAMINATED MATERIALS. AFTER FREEWAYS WERE CLEAN PERSONNEL EXCAVATED FOUR CONTAMINATED AREAS TOOK SAMPLES AND BACKFILLED THE EXCATED AREAS. PRESSURE WASHING THE OVER PASS WAS ALSO DONE. TXDOT PERSONNEL INSPECTED THE SITE AND STATED NO FURTHER CLEANUP WAS NECESSARY.

column14: ON RAMP HWY 104 ON TO I-71
column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: WHILE TRAVELING IN A RAIN STORM, DRIVER TOOK ENTRANCE RAMP ONTO I-71 FROM HWY 104 TOO FAST, HYDROPLANED, LOST CONTROL AND OVERTURNED. MATERIAL WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER CARGO TANK AND APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED DURING TRANSFER, LEAKING TRANSFER HOSES AND SPILLS DURING DISCONNECT. RELEASED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP AND MATERIAL AND OTHER CONTAMINATES REMOVED FROM THE SITE AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF. OHIO EPA ON SITE DURING THIS TRANSFER AND CLEANUP. THERE WAS NO PACKAGE FAILURE. AFTER MATERIAL WAS TRANSFERRED THE VEHICLE WAS UP-RIGHTED AND REMOVED FROM THE ACCIDENT SCENE AND WILL REMAIN OUT OF SERVICE UNTIL REPAIRS ARE COMPLETE. ENTRANCE RAMP WAS CLOSED FOR 12.5 HOURS. THERE WERE NO EVACUATIONS. DRIVER REFUSED MEDICAL TREATMENT AT THE ACCIDENT SCENE BUT IS BEING TREATED BY A DOCTOR AT HIS HOME TOWN. INJURIES ARE THE RESULT OF THE COLLISION AND NOT THE RESULT OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.
NO REMARKS

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. DURING ROUTINE INSPECTION, FREE PRODUCT WAS DISCOVERED DRIPPING FROM THE LOCK BETWEEN THE TRAILERS. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM CONTAINED THE FREE PRODUCT TO THE CEMENT USING BOOMS. HAZMAT ONE OF OLATHE, KANSAS WAS CONTACTED TO COORDINATE THE CLEANUP. HAZMAT ONE CONTACTED ONYX OF BROOKLINE PARK, MINNESOTA TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT ONE, ONE-HUNDRED AND NINETEEN GALLON ALUMINUM TOTE WAS LEAKING. APPROXIMATELY EIGHTY GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND AFFECTED THE PALLETS OF OTHER SHIPMENTS. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE VALVE. ONYX PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING ABSORBENTS AND BOOMS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND AFFECTED PALLETS WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION. THE VALVE ON THE TOTE WAS TIGHTENED AND IT WILL BE FORWARDED ON WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE ON THE DOCK, ONE CARDBOARD CARTON CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT. UPON INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE JUG WAS LEAKING AND THE REMAINING THREE JUGS WERE UNAFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY ONE-QUARTER GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. THE TERMINAL TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES AND ABSORBENTS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND THE DAMAGED JUG WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON PLASTIC  PAIL, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE DRIVER LOADED THE TRAILER AT THE PRYOR FACILITY ON FRIDAY EVENING, JULY 25,2003. HE THEN DEPARTED THE FACILITY AND DROVE TO THE COMFORT INN LOCATED IN THE PRYOR AREA, APPROXIMATELY 4 MILES FROM THE PLANT. UPON ARRIVING AT THE MOTEL, HE CHECKED ALL VALVE POSITIONS IN THE PUMPING CABINET, PLACED A PADLOCK ON THE CABINET DOOR, AND  RETIRED TO HIS ROOM AT 1840 HRS. AT APPROXIMATELY 0640 HRS., ON SATURDAY MORNING, JULY 26, HE WAS INFORMED THAT THERE WAS AN EVIDENT PROBLEM WITH HIS TRAILER. HE IMMEDIATELY RESPONDED TO DISCOVER A VAPOR CLOUD AND LIQUID ESCAPING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER, WHICH APPARENTLY HAD BEEN ESCAPING FOR SOME TIME AS THE ICE BUILDUP ON THE PAVEMENT COVERED A LARGE AREA. THE DRIVER RETRIEVED A BUCKET OF WATER FROM THE MOTEL TO THAW THE PADLOCK IN ORDER TO GAIN ACCESS TO THE VALVE CABINET. HE OPENED THE CABINET DOOR AND SECURED THE BOTTOM FILL VALVE TO STOP THE LEAK. THE FILL VALVE APPARENTLY HAD ICE UNDER THE VALVE WHEN CLOSING AT THE END OF THE FILL, WHICH ALLOWED LIQUID TO ESCAPE AFTER THAWING. THE DRIVER'S RESPONSIVE ACTIONS RESOLVED THE SITUATION OF THE LEAK IMMEDIATELY. THE DRIVER ALSO NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR IMMEDIATELY WHO IN TURN, NOTIFIED THE ON-CALL MECHANIC TO RESPOND TO ASSIST IN SECURING THE EQUIPMENT AND ALLOWING MOVEMENT TO THE FACILITY. PAST TRAINING FOR ALL THOSE INVOLVED PROVED TO BE EFFECTIVE IN PREVENTING A POSSIBLE HAZARDOUS INCIDENT FROM GETTING OUT OF HAND.

TRANSFERRING FROM TRUCK TO CONSIGNEES' STORAGE TANK.  UNKNOWN TO DRIVER THE TANK HAD A HOLE IN IT.  CONSIGNEE OPERATOR STOPPED DRIVER AFTER 2-5 GALLONS RAN INTO CONTAINMENT AREA AND CONSIGNEE CLEANED UP.

WHILE TRANSPORTING THE LOAD OF HAZARDOUS WASTE TO THE TRANSPORTERS TRANSFER FACILITY, THE DRUMS OF ACID BEGAN TO BUILD UP PRESSURE IN THE DRUM.  ONE OF THE SULFURIC ACID DRUMS STARTED TO BECOME ROUND ON THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM AND FELL OVER IN THE VAN AS THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE TRANSFER FACILITY. WHEN THE DRUM TIPPED OVER THE DRUM SPLIT IN THE SEAM OF THE DRUM TO RELEASE SOME THE PRESSURE.  THE SULFURIC ACID SPRAYED ALL OVER THE INSIDE OF THE TRUCK AND ON TO THE GROUND.  THE MATERIAL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP AND THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM FOR TRANSPORTATION.  ALL OF THE ACID DRUMS ON THIS MANIFEST HAD TO BE VENTED AS THEY HAD BUILT UP PRESSURE.  ONCE THEY ALL HAD BEEN VENTED ALL OF THE DRUMS WERE PLACED IN SALVAGE DRUMS AND DELIVER TO THE CONSIGNEE WITHOUT ANY FURTHER INCIDENTS. ALL OF THE MATERIAL FROM THE CLEAN UP WAS CONTAINERIZED AND WILL BE DISPOSED IN ACCORDANCE WITH ALL FEDERAL AND STATE REGULATION.

column168: DRIVER WAS CHECKING HIS VEHICLE AFTER AN OVERNIGHT STOP.  HE OBSERVED LIQUID ON THE GROUND UNDER HIS TRAILER.  HE INVESTIGATED AND FOUND A SHIPMENT OF PAILS OF PRODUCT STACKED THREE HIGH ON PALLETS.  THE PAILS DID NOT EXTEND TO THE FULL DIMENSIONS OF THE PALLETS, LEAVING GAPS BETWEEN THE STACKS.  THE STACKS WERE LOOSELY SHRINK WRAPPED BY THE SHIPPER.  SEVERAL PAILS HAD FALLEN INTO THE GAPS, AND ONE PAIL HAD BEEN PUNCTURED.  IT WAS NEARLY EMPTY.  MOST OF THE MATERIAL WAS STILL ON THE TRAILER FLOOR, BUT A SMALL QUANTITY HAD ESCAPED TO THE GROUND.  THE DRIVER USED PADS AND BOOMS FROM HIS SPILL KIT TO CONTAIN THE SPILLAGE.  HE ACQUIRED SOME OIL DRY FROM THE TRUCK STOP MANAGEMENT WHICH HE USED TO ABSORB THE FREE LIQUIDS ON THE TRAILER FLOOR AND ON THE GROUND.  HE SHOVELED THE SOLIDIFIED MATERIAL INTO SOME PLASTIC BAGS.  HE TOOK THE BAGS AND THE SHIPMENT TO THE CARRIER'S NEAREST FACILITY.

CARRIER'S DRIVER WAS MAKING ONE OF SEVERAL DELIVERIES.  IN ORDER TO ACCESS THEIR SHIPMENT, IT WAS NECESSARY FOR A FORKLIFT OPERATOR TO USE A DRUM PICK TO MOVE SOME DRUMS OF H/M THAT WERE DESTINED FOR ANOTHER LOCATION. ON SITE EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL HANDLED ALL ASPECTS OF CLEAN UP AND DISPOSAL OF THE WASTE.

DURING DELIVERY, THE CONSIGNEE'S UNLOADER OBSERVED DAMPNESS AROUND THE BUNGS OF THREE DRUMS.  THEY DID NOT ATTEMPT TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE OR TO CORRECT THE CONDITION.  THEY ACCEPTED THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT WITH A NOTATION OF THE CONDITION.

DRIVER NOTES THAT WHEN HE BEGAN HIS DAY HE DETECT AN ODOR IN HIS TRAILER, BUT DID NOT ATTACH ANY SIGNIFICANCE TO IT.  AT THE STOP PRIOR TO THE CONSIGNEE HE TOOK DOWN SOME PLYWOOD THAT WAS BEING USED TO SECURE OTHER FREIGHT INTO THE TRAILER.  AT THAT TIME HE SAW A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID COMING FROM THE SIDE OF ONE DRUM.  AS HE WAS LESS THAN ONE MILE FROM THE CONSIGNEE, HE ELECTED TO CONTINUE TO THEIR LOCATION. THE CONSIGNEE UNLOADED THE SHIPMENT AND FOUND A CRACK IN A DENT IN ONE DRUM.  THEIR IN-HOUSE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND TOOK CONTROL OF THE SITUATION.  THEY OVERPACKED THE LEAKING DRUM.  NOTING THAT THE OTHER DRUM IN THE SHIPMENT HAD ARRIVED UPSIDE DOWN, THEY OVERPACKED IT AS WELL.  THEY RETAINED BOTH.  THEY UNLOADED THE REST OF THE FREIGHT IN THE CARRIER'S TRAILER AND TOOK TO AN ON-SITE WASHOUT FACILITY.  AFTER WASHING OUT THE TRAILER FLOOR, THEY RETURNED IT TO THE LOADING DOCK AND RELOADED IT.  THE DRIVER CONTINUED ON HIS WAY.

column168: CARRIER'S DOCK SUPERVISOR REPORTED THAT ONE IBC IN A SHIPMENT ARRIVED AT THE FACILITY WITH SOME LEAKAGE ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  HE AND THE UNLOADER FOUND THAT A FILL PORT CLOSURE WAS NOT ON.  THEY LOCATED THE CLOSURE AND PUT IT BACK ON, BUT WERE UNABLE TO GET IT TO TIGHTEN PROPERLY.  THE CARRIER'S HAZMAT TECHNICIAN INSTRUCTED  THEM TO HOLD THE PACKAGE ON THE DOCK IN A SECURE LOCATION UNTIL THE SHIPPER COULD BE CONTACTED FOR SPECIFIC INSTRUCTIONS.  DOCK PERSONNEL USED OIL DRY TO SOLIDIFY THE MATERIAL WHICH THEY THEN PUT INTO  PLASTIC BAGS.  THE BAGS WERE PLACED WITH THE DEFECTIVE PACKAGE TO BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSAL.

column168: SHIPMENT WAS ON THE SHIPPER'S SHRINK WRAPPED PALLETS.  THE SHIPPER HAD LOADED TWO 55-GALLON DRUMS AND A NUMBER OF 5-GALLON PAILS ONTO ONE PALLET. THE CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT WITH A NOTATION OF ITS CONDITION.

column168: DRIVER HAD STOPPED AT A TRUCK STOP FOR A REST BREAK.  WHILE CHECKING HIS VEHICLE, HE OBSERVED A VISCOUS, STRINGY LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER.  HE BELIEVED THAT THE LEAKING CONTAINER WAS IN THE FRONT OF A FULLY LOADED TRAILER.  CARRIER'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN RETAINED THE SERVICES OF A CONTRACTOR TO MITIGATE THE SITUATION.  UPON ARRIVAL, THE CONTRACTOR'S PERSONNEL MADE ENTRY INTO THE TRAILER.  THEY WERE ABLE TO WORK THEIR WAY TO THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER.  THEY FOUND A PORTABLE TANK OF A RESIN SOLUTION WITH A 2" FILL CAP MISSING.  PRODUCT HAD BEEN ESCAPING THROUGH THE OPEN PORT AS THE VEHICLE WAS MOVING ON THE HIGHWAY.  THEY LOCATED THE CAP WHICH HAD FALLEN OFF, AND REPLACED IT.  THEY SOLIDIFIED THE MATERIAL REMAINING ON THE TRAILER FLOOR WITH OIL DRY.  THEY ALSO CLEANED UP THE MATERIAL THAT HAD LEAKED ONTO THE TRUCK STOP PARKING LOT.  THE VEHICLE WAS THEN ABLE TO PROCEED TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY FOR INSPECTION AND ADDITIONAL CLEANING.

ON ARRIVAL AT THE CONSIGNEE, THE DRIVER TEAM FOUND A SHIPMENT OF SIX PAILS ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  FIVE OF THE SIX WERE BULGED OUT AT THE BOTTOMS AND HAD SPLIT SEAMS.  PRODUCT HAD LEAKED OUT TO THE LEVEL OF THE OPENINGS.  AS THE MATERIAL EVAPORATED RAPIDLY, THERE WAS NOT ANY DISCERNABLE ESCAPE OF PRODUCT FROM THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVERS NOTED THAT THERE ARE NO MARKINGS ON THE PACKAGES STATING THAT THE PRODUCT IS TO BE STORED IN A COOL, DRY PLACE. THEY NOTE THAT TWO DAYS EARLIER WHILE PASSING THROUGH FLAGSTAFF, ARIZ, AREA, THE AMBIENT TEMPERATURE WAS COOL.  HOWEVER, THE NEXT DAY, WHILE CROSSING THE CALIFORNIA DESERT, THE TEMPERATURE REACHED 114F. THEY BELIEVE THE EXTREME TEMPERATURE CHANGES DURING THE TRIP WERE AT LEAST PARTIALLY RESPONSIBLE FOR THE CONDITION OF THE SHIPMENT.  THE TEAM USED MATERIAL FROM THEIR SPILL KIT TO ABSORBED THE REMAINING STANDING LIQUID.  THEY OVERPACKED THE PAILS AND TOOK THEM TO THE CARRIER'S NEARBY FACILITY.

THERE WAS ALREADY APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF PRODUCT ON THE GROUND WHEN WE PERFORMED OUR INBOUND INSPECTION. column168: SHIPMENT IS DESCRIBED SIMPLY AS "A/C PARTS FOR REPAIR.  NOT RESTRICTED TO DGR" ON THE AWB DOCUMENT.  UPON BREAKDOWN FROM THE EXPRESS CONTAINER AMP35764LH, OUT IMPORT WAREHOUSE AGENT NOTICED LEAKAGE FROM THIS PACKAGE ONTO THE ULD FLOOR.  THE LEAKAGE LIQUID HAD A STRONG SMELL, SIMILAR TO THAT OF FUEL.  HE STOWED THE LEAKING PACKAGE IN THE IMPORT DGR AREA OF THE WAREHOUSE, SUSPECTING THAT IT CONTAINED UNDECLARED DGR, AND NOTIFIED AN IMPORT SUPERVISOR.  THE IMPORT SUPERVISOR OPENED THE PACKAGE TO FIND AN AIRCRAFT PART, AND THE INNER PACKAGING OF THE SPECIAL TRANSPORT BOX COMPLETELY SOAKED WITH AIRCRAFT FUEL OF KEROSENE.  I WOULD ESTIMATE THAT AT LEASE 0.25L OF LIQUID HAD LEAKED OUT OF THIS AIRCRAFT PART.  PHOTOS OF THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION ARE ON FILE.  LUFTHANSA CARGO SUBSEQUENTLY NOTIFIED THE FAA OF THIS INCIDENT, WHO DISPATCHED AN ANALYST TO COLLECT A SAMPLE OF THE LIQUID.  ANALYSIS OF THIS SUBSTANCE PROVED IT TO BE RESTRICTED ACCORDING THE IATA DANGEROUS GOODS REGULATIONS.

EMPLOYEE TRAINING IS BEING IMPLEMENTED TO HELP INSURE THAT A CATASTROPHIC COLLISION LIKE THIS IS NOT REPEATED.

column168: ACFX 82775, A LOADED TWO-COMPARTMENT TANK CAR, WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING STEADILY FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE ON THE B END COMPARTMENT. CAR WAS LOCATED IN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN BALDWIN, FL. CSXT NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, MARATHON ASHLAND AND DISPATCHED A CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER AND AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR. THE MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT PLACED A 5-GAL BUCKET UNDER THE CAR TO CONTAIN THE LEAKING PRODUCT. CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS REPRESENTATIVE FOUND THE CAR LEAKING FROM TOP OF THE BELL CAP WHERE THE OUTLET EXTENSION PIPE SCREWS INTO IT. THE OPERATING HANDLE FOR THE BOTTOM OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS IN THE CLOSED AND PINNED POSITION. THE BOTTOM OUTLET WAFER VALVE WAS OPENED AND CLOSED THREE TIMES IN AN EFFORT TO RESTART THE VALVE, BUT THE LEAKAGE RATE DID NOT CHANGE. ABSORBENT PADS WERE TAPED AROUND THE VALVE AND A PLASTIC BAG WAS SECURED OVER THE VALVE SO THAT THE CAR COULD BE CUT OUT OF A TRAIN AND ISOLATED. WHEN THE CAR WAS ISOLATED, THE BELL CAP WAS TIGHTENED ABOUT 1/4 TO 1/2 TURN BUT THE LEAK DID NOT STOP. WITH MARATHON ASHLAND'S CONCURRENCE, THE PRODUCT IN THE B END COMPARTMENT WAS TRANSLOADED INTO 2 TANK TRUCKS. THE LEAK STOPPED WHEN COMPARTMENT WAS EMPTIED. THE TRUCKS DELIVERED THE PRODUCT TO THE SHIPPER'S FACILITIES IN DORAVILLE, GA AND SAVANNAH, GA. THE BELL CAP WAS REMOVED AND WAS FOUND TO HAVE 2 GASKETS IN IT. A NEW GASKET WAS INSERTED AND THE BELL CAP WAS INSTALLED WRENCH TIGHT. ON JULY 23, 2003, THE SECOND COMPARTMENT (THE A END COMPARTMENT) WAS TRANSLOADED INTO 2 TANK TRUCKS MAKING THE TANK CAR EMPTY. THE CAR WAS RELEASED AND TRANSPORTED BACK TO MARATHON ASHLAND FOR INSPECTION.

A SUPERVISOR CONTACTED THE ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE TEAM TO CHECK A CONTAINER SHE HAD ISOLATED DUE TO MOISTURE SHE HAD SEEN AROUND THE CAP.  THE TEAM RESPONDED AND DETERMINED THAT THE LEAKAGE WAS DUE TO THE DRUM HAVING A LOOSE CAP.  THE CAP WAS TIGHTENED AND THE CONTAINER'S EXTERIOR THOROUGHLY CLEANED.  THE SHIPMENT WAS TURNED BACK OVER TO THE AREA SUPERVISOR TO CONTINUE DELIVERY.

ON 07/18/03, A TRANSFORMER WAS NOTICED TO BE LEAKING ON AN ONYX TRUCK WHILE PARKED AT AN ONYX TEN-DAY TRANSFER FACILITY IN MENOMONEE FALLS, WI AT APPROXIMATELY 8:00 AM.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TRANSFORMER WAS LEAKING THROUGH A CRACKED BUSHING.  THE TRANSFORMER WAS OVERPACKED AND THE TRUCK WAS DECONNED USING DIESEL FUEL.  THE WOODEN FLOOR SECTIONS OF THE TRUCK WERE REMOVED AND SENT TO A TSCA INCINERATOR ALONG WITH WIPES GENERATOR DURING THE CLEAN-UP  THE CONCENTRATION OF PCBS'S IN THE OIL THAT SPILLED WAS 63 PPM.  THE TRANSFORMER WAS INSPECTED PRIOR TO SHIPMENT AND NO DEFECTS WERE NOTED.  ADDITIONAL TRAINING WILL BE CONDUCTED FOR ALL FIELD PERSONNEL INCLUDING OVERPACKING OF TRANSFORMERS.

THE DRIVER WAS IN THE LOADING PROCESS WHEN THE CUSTOMERS LOADING COMPUTER SYSTEM FAILED.  THE FLOW METER ON THE COMPUTER SYSTEM FAILED TO CALCULATE TO AMOUNT OF PRODUCT BEING LOADED.  WHEN THE PRODUCT REACHED THE PROBE IT FAILED TO SHUT THE SYSTEM DOWN. THE DRIVER HAS NO WAY OF KNOWING HOW MUCH PRODUCT IS IN THE CARGO TANK UNTIL HE REMOVES THE LOADING PIPE.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY TRIPPED THE EMERGENCY SHUT DOWN WHEN HE SAW THE PRODUCT START TO FLOW OUT OF THE DOME LID OPENING.  THE PLANT OPERATOR WAS IN THE CONTROL ROOM AT THE TIME THE COMPUTER SYSTEM MALFUNCTIONED.  THE PLANT ASSUMED ALL RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE OVERFLOW AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL.  PLANT PERSONNEL REPAIRED THE PROBLEM WITH THE LOADING SYSTEM.

column168: THE DRIVER HAD ACTIVATED THE COMPUTER LOADING SYSTEM DURING A RAIN STORM WITH LIGHTING.  A BOLT OF LIGHTING STRUCK AND CAUSED A POWER OUTAGE FOR A BRIEF PERIOD OF TIME.  WHEN THE POWER CAME BACK UP THE SYSTEM RECOGNIZED IT HAD BEEN PREVIOUSLY ACTIVATED IT STARTED LOADING WITHOUT THE USE OF THE DEADMAN SWITCH.  THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO MANUAL SHUT DOWN THE PROCESS.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER PROCEDURE FOR LOADING.  HAD THE DRIVER NOT ACTIVATED THE COMPUTER SYSTEM UNTIL THE LOADING PIPE WAS INSTALLED IN THE CARGO TANK THIS INCIDENT WOULD NOT HAVE OCCURRED.  THE COMPUTER SHOULD HAVE BEEN ACTIVATED AFTER THE LOADING PIPE IS IN PLACE.  CTL SENT OUT A CREW TO CHIP UP THE HARDEN SULFUR.

KELLEY DRIVER NOTICE FREE PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE CARGO TANKER. APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED FROM THE CARGO TANKER. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LEAKING LINER IN THE CARGO TANKER. THE JACK B KELLEY DRIVER APPLIED SAND TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT TO THE AFFECTED ASPHALT SURFACE. LCM CORPORATION OF ROANOKE, VIRGINIA WAS CONTACTED T COMPLETED THE CLEANUP. LCM CORPORATION PLACED A PLASTIC POOL UNDER THE LEAK TO CONTAIN ANY FURTHER RELEASE OF FREE PRODUCT UNTIL THEY COULD RETURN THE FOLLOWING DAY TO COMPLETE THE PRODUCT TRANSFER. LCM CORPORATION RETURNED TO THE SITE ON JULY 22,2002 AND USED A COMPRESSOR TO TRANSFER THE REMAINING PRODUCT INTO A NEW CARGO TANKER. THEE WAS A RAIN OCCURRENCE OVER NIGHT, WHICH CAUSED THE POOL OF HYDROBROMIC ACID IMPACTED WATER TO OVERFLOW BACK N THE ASPHALT. LCM CORPORATION APPLIED ADDITIONAL ABSORBENTS TO CONTAIN AND REMOVE THE PRODUCT FROM THE AFFECTED ASPHALT SURFACE. LCM CORPORATION PLACED THE HYROBROMIC ACID IMPACTED ABSORBENTS INTO THREE RECOVERY DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL. LCM CORPORATION WILL COORDINATE DISPOSAL OF THE THREE DRUMS OF HYDROBROMIC ACID IMPACTED ABSORBENTS. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ON NOVEMBER 18, 2003, OLIN CORP ADVISED CSX TRANSPORTATION OF A CONDITION REPORTED TO THEM BY THEIR CUSTOMER, E I DUPONT OF AMPTHILL, VA.  OVER THE COURSE OF THE PAST YEAR AND ONE HALF, DUPONT HAS DISCOVERED SMALL AMOUNTS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE RESIDUE AROUND THE BASE OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD) ON 39 TANK CARS AFTER THEY HAD BEEN UNLOADED AT THE AMPTHILL, VA FACILITY.  ALL OF THE CARS ARE EQUIPPED WITH MIDLAND EXTERNAL PRD AND THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE TO INDICATE THE RESIDUE PRESENT WAS THE RESULT OF A PRODUCT RELEASE DURING TRANSPORTATION.  OLIN INSPECTED AND TESTED SEVERAL OF THE PRD'S AND FOUND NO MECHANICAL PROBLEMS OR DEFECTS WITH THEM.  OLIN REQUESTED CSXT'S ASSISTANCE TO REVIEW THE ROUTING AND HANDLING OF THEIR TANK CARS TRANSPORTED TO DUPONT'S  AMPTHILL, VA PLANT.  THE ROUTING INDICATED THE CARS SHIPPED FROM OLIN'S NIAGARA FALLS, NY PLANT WERE SWITCHED AT CSXT'S RAIL YARDS IN NIAGARA FALLS, NY, SELKIRK, NY, RICHMOND, VA, AND BELLWOOD, VA FOR DELIVERY TO DUPONT AT AMPTHILL.  THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE FROM CSXT, DUPONT OR OLIN THAT ANY OF THE CARS IN QUESTION HAD EXPERIENCED ANY UNUSUAL HANDLING OR HARD COUPLING'S IN TRANSIT.  CSXT WITH OLIN'S CORPORATION HAD INITIATED A PLAN TO EQUIP SEVERAL TANK CARS WITH IMPACT RECORDERS THAT WILL MONITOR COUPLING IMPACTS TO DETERMINE IF CAR HANDLING COULD BE A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR IN A POSSIBLE PRODUCT RELEASE FROM THE PRD'S. THE STUDY WILL BEGIN THE LATTER PART OF DECEMBER AND WILL CONTINUE INTO THE FIRST QUARTER OF 2004.  EVEN THOUGH THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE THAT THE RESIDUE DISCOVERED AROUND THE PRD'S WAS DUE TO A PRODUCT RELEASE IN TRANSIT, CSXT IS SUBMITTING THIS REPORT IN ACCORDANCE WITH SECTION 171.16 OF THE US DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION HAZARDOUS MATERIALS REGULATIONS, 49 CFR.

ON JULY 1ST, 2003 AN OSMOSE EMPLOYEE WAS DRIVING AN OSMOSE 3/4 TON FORD TRUCK ON AN ELECTRIC UTILITY'S RIGHT OF WAY WHEN THE TRUCK BECAME STUCK. THE DRIVER GOT OUT OF THE VEHICLE TO ACCESS THE SITUATION AND REMOVE SOIL FROM AROUND THE REAR TIRES.  WHEN HE LOOKED UP HE NOTICED THE DRIVER-SIDE OF THE TRUCK, BY THE DOOR, WAS ON FIRE.  THE FIRE SPREAD THROUGH THE REST OF THE VEHICLE AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED TO CONTAIN AND EXTINGUISH THE FIRE.  LATER INSPECTION WOULD SHOW A LEAKING FUEL LINE AS THE CAUSE OF THE FIRE.  AN ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN-UP COMPANY WAS CALLED TO CLEAN THE TRUCK AND THE SURROUNDING AREA.  THE MATERIAL ENCLOSED IN THE BACK OF THE TRUCK NEVER EXITED THE VEHICLE, HOWEVER THERE WAS CONCERN THAT TRACE AMOUNTS OF THE MATERIAL MAY HAVE RUN OFF THE VEHICLE WITH THE WATER USED TO PUT OUT THE FIRE.  SOME OF THE MATERIAL WHICH WAS STILL IN USEABLE CONDITION WAS REMOVED FROM THE VEHICLE WITH THE WATER USED TO PUT OUT THE FIRE.  SOME OF THE MATERIAL WHICH WAS STILL IN USEABLE CONDITION WAS REMOVED FROM THE VEHICLE BY COMPANY PERSONNEL.  THE REMAINDER OF MATERIAL WHICH COULD NOT BE RECOVERED WAS DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH APPLICABLE REGULATIONS.  THE AREA OF SOIL AFFECTED BY THE WATER DISCHARGE FROM THE FIRE WAS EXCAVATED FROM BETWEEN 4 AND 6 INCHES IN DEPTH.  SAMPLES OF THE SOIL WERE TESTED AT A LAB FOR CONTAMINANTS AND NO APPRECIABLE AMOUNTS OF MATERIAL WERE FOUND.  THE SITE WAS DETERMINED TO BE CLEAN AND THE EXCAVATED AREA WAS FILLED IN WITH CLEAN SOIL.  WASTE FROM THE CLEAN UP WAS SENT TO A LICENSED WASTE DISPOSAL FACILITY AND THE VEHICLE WAS REPLACED BY THE MANUFACTURER.  DUE TO THE NATURE AND CAUSE OF THE FIRE, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE FIRE WAS NOT THE FAULT OF THE DRIVER AND OUTSIDE HIS ABILITY TO CONTROL.  SAFETY PROCEDURES IN PLACE AT THE TIME AND THE QUICK RESPONSE BY THE DRIVER HELPED TO LIMIT THE AREA AFFECTED BY THE FIRE TO ONLY THE AREA AROUND THE VEHICLE.  NO NEW SAFETY PROCEDURES ARE NECESSARY AT THIS TIME.

UNDECLARED LEAKING PACKAGE DISCOVERED IN UPS FACILITY.

IX. DESCRIPTION OF EVENTS.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0815 HOURS, 7-7-03, DAVE PITNER, LOGISTICS COORDINATOR, APRIA HEALTHCARE, LIVERMORE, CA. DAVE, WHILE OPENING THE BRANCH FOUND THAT SUBJECT(S) UNKNOWN HAD SLIGHTLY OPENED A FILL ON A FILL LINE FROM THEIR 3000 GAL. STAND TANK OVER THE WEEKEND, RESULTING IN 75" OF OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID (LOX) TO DRAIN OUT ONTO THE CONCRETE CATCH PAD.  ENTRY WAS MADE TO THE ENCLOSURE AND THE VALVE WAS TURNED OFF. THE AREA WAS SECURED WHILE THE RESIDUAL EVAPORATED.  THERE WAS NO COLLATERAL DAMAGE AND NO INJURIES.  THE STAND TANK IS LOCATED IN A SECURED CINDER BLOCK ENCLOSURE WITH STEEL DOORS.  PITNER STATES THAT WHILE CLOSING THE BRANCH ON THURSDAY JULY 3RD, 2003, HE HAD PERSONALLY INSPECTED THE STAND TANK.  WHILE HE DID NOT ENTER THE ENCLOSURE, HE VERIFIED THAT THE DOORS WERE LOCKED.  HE STATES THAT THERE WAS NO FOG OR ANY INDICATION THAT THERE WAS ANY LEAK.  THE TANK HAD NOT BEEN USED SINCE FILLING THE TMVS IN THE BRANCHES TRUCKS THAT MORNING.  THIS OPERATION WAS COMPLETED AT APPROXIMATELY 0900 HOURS.  UPON COMPLETION OF THE FILLING PROCESS THE DOORS TO THE TANK ENCLOSURE HAD BEEN LOCKED.  IF THERE HAD BEEN ANY LEAK IT WOULD HAVE BEEN EVIDENT IN THAT AMOUNT OF TIME.  EXAMINATION OF THE TANK ENCLOSURE FOUND INDICATION THAT SOMEONE MAY HAVE CLIMBED THE WALL.

DARYLL LAJAUNIE, FOREMAN GENERAL-LIVONIA, CONTACTED RMCC FROM HIS OFFICE. WITH HIM IN HIS OFFICE WAS TOM ROBINSON, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, AND JIM DUNCAN, FRA HAZMAT INSPECTOR.  IT WAS REPORTED BY MR. DUNCAN THAT, WHILE CONDUCTING INSPECTIONS, HE DISCOVERED TANKCAR CALX 3035 WAS LEAKING.  THE TANKCAR WAS IN THE LIVONIA YARD IN YARD 1 TRACK 098 AND WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP POSSIBLY FROM TWO PLACES, AROUND THE MANWAY COVER AND THE VACUUM BREAKER.  THERE WAS NO PRODUCT ON THE GROUND AND POSSIBLY ON A HALF A GALLON IN THE RAILCAR BODY.  HE REPORTED NO INJURIES OR EVACUATIONS.  THE PRODUCT WAS DESCRIBED AS A WAXY SUBSTANCE.  MR. ROBINSON REPORTED THEY WOULD BE RESPONDING TO INSPECT THE CAR.  MGR. ROBINSON DETERMINED THAT THE CAR WAS NOT ACTIVELY LEAKING, BUT IT APPEARED THAT PRODUCT MAY HAVE SLOSHED DURING TRANSIT.  THE PRODUCT WAS DESCRIBED AS HAVING A SYRUP CONSISTENCY.  ONE OF EIGHT MANWAY BOLTS WAS FOUND TO BE LOOSE AND POSSIBLY TWO OR LESS OUNCES HAD LEAKED FROM THAT SITE AND ABOUT A QUART HAD LEAKED FROM THE VACUUM BREAKER UNDER THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING. MGR. ROBINSON TIGHTENED THE ONE LOOSE MANWAY BOLT.  THE TWO INCH LIQUID VALVE PLUG WAS TIGHTENED, BUT THE VALVE WAS STILL OPEN.   RMCC CONFERRED MGR. ROBINSON WITH BILL HUFFMAN, SCOTT COMPANY.  MR.  HUFFMAN WAS SUPPLIED INFORMATION AND WAS INFORMED A CONTRACTOR WOULD BE RESPONDING AT THEIR COST.  HULCHER SERVICES, CONTRACTOR, RESPONDED AND REMOVED A DEFECTIVE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE AND INSTALLED A PLUG.  HULCHER ALSO CLEANED UP THE MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT SPLLED ONTO THE BODY OF THE TANKCAR,  LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED.

column168: APPROXIMATELY 8:15 P.M. PETER KOBER ATLANTA TANK FARM SUPERVISOR REPORTED TO ME VIA PHONE THAT A UNIVAR WAREHOUSE EMPLOYEE HAD TURNED OVER A TOTE CONTAINING WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID N.O.S (XYLENE & NAPTHA) RESULTING IN THE LOSS OF ABOUT 260 GALLONS ONTO THE CONCRETE EMPTY TOTE STORAGE AREA, AND THE GROUND JUST BEHIND THIS STORAGE AREA. I ARRIVED AT THE BRANCH AT ABOUT 9 P.M. AND ACCESSED THE SITUATION. I THEN CALLED HEPACO, AN ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE AND REMEDIATION COMPANY TO DO THE CLEAN UP. AFTER GETTING HEPACO IN ROUTE I CALLED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER & EPD. I SPOKE TO MR. WHITE AT THE NCR AND HE GAVE ME A CASE NUMBER OF 649787. I ALSO ADVISED HIM THAT HEPACO WAS IN ROUTE TO DO THE CLEAN UP. I SPOKE TO HARRY AT THE STATE EPD AND HE GAVE ME A CASE NUMBER ALSO OF 070203-22. AT APPROXIMATELY 11 P.M. RICHARD DOLLAR, THE SUPERVISOR FOR HEPACO ARRIVED ON THE SCENE. HIS CREW WAS ALSO IN ROUTE WITH THEIR EQUIPMENT AND A VACUUM TRUCK. A SHORT TIME LATER, MARY SMILEY, EPD CALLED AND ASKED IF THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND WHO THE CONTRACTOR WAS. I TOLD HER WE HAVE AT THIS TIME BEEN ABLE TO DAM UP THE SPILL AND THAT HEPACO WAS HERE. AT APPROXIMATELY 12:00 A.M. THE REMAINDER OF THE HEPACO CREW ARRIVED AND WE CONDUCTED THE UNIVAR CONTRACTOR HAZCOM AND HELD A SAFETY MEETING TO REVIEW MSDS'S GROUNDING, PPE, ETC. FOR THE CLEAN UP WORK. THE CLEAN UP BEGAN SHORTLY THERE AFTER. THE HEPACO CREW WORKED THE SCENE FOR THE NEXT 24 HOURS ( BEGAN ABOUT 2 A.M. THURSDAY AND LEFT AROUND 2 A.M. FRIDAY). FINAL COUNT WAS 85 DRUMS OF LIQUID WATER , XYLENE, AND NAPTHA, 1 DRUM OF PPE & PIGS, AND 1 ROLL OFF CONTAINER JUST UNDER 1/2 FULL. THE WASTES WILL BE SENT TO PCI IN MILLINGTON TN. THEIR EPA NUMBER IS TND000772186. THE LIQUID WASTE WILL BE DISPOSED OF AS FUEL BLENDING AND THE DIRT IN THE ROLL OFF WILL BE LAND FILLED.

column168: ON JULY 7TH, 2003, CENEX DRIVER PAUL LATKA WAS DELIVERING A LOAD OF FUEL TO FARMERS UNION OIL COMPANY IN TERRY, MT.  THE DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO DELIVER 7400 GALLONS OF #2 DYED DIESEL FUEL INTO VERTICAL TANK#2 AT THE BULK PLANT.  INSTEAD OF UNLOADING INTO TANK #2, THE DRIVER UNLOADED INTO 2 COMPARTMENTS OF A 3-COMPARTMENT HORIZONTAL TANK INTO TANKS 6 & 7 WHICH ALSO STORE #2 DYED DIESEL.  TANK 6 & 7 WOULD NOT HOLD THE 7400 GALLONS OF DYED DIESEL AND THESE TANKS WERE OVERFILLED RESULTING IN A SPILL OF 774 GALLONS WITHIN THE CONTAINMENT AREA OF THE BULK PLANT. THE COMPANY IMMEDIATELY RESPONDED TO THE SPILL AND NOTIFIED THE NRC & SERC.  THE SITE HAS BEEN COMPLETELY REMEDIATED AND ALL CONTAMINATED SOILS HAVE BEEN DISPOSED OF. ALL TANKS (UG) HAVE BEEN PROPERLY IDENTIFIED W/PRODUCT ID TAGS AND MAXIMUM FILL HEIGHTS TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENT.

WHILE PASSING TRAIN Q37518 THE CREW OF K95119 OBSERVED A FOG-LIKE VAPOR CLOUD AND EVIDENCE OF FROSTING ON THE EXTERIOR OF THE VALUE CONTROL BOX OF TANK CAR APHX 2014. THE TRAIN (Q37518) WAS BROUGHT SAFELY TO A STOP ON THE WESTBOUND MAIN TRACK IN THE YARD AT BRUNSWICK, MD. THE TRAIN CREW OBSERVED A HEAVY VAPOR CLOUD COMING FROM THE VALVE CONTROL BOX LOCATED ON THE SIDE, LOWER HALF OF THE CAR. PERSONNEL AT THE YARD CONTACTED THE APPROPRIATE PARTIES AND INITIATED ISOLATION AROUND THE AREA OF THE CAR. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE STATE DEPARTMENT OF THE ENVIRONMENT WERE NOTIFIED OF THE SITUATION. CSX HAZMAT PERSONNEL ALONG WITH MEMBERS OF THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ENTERED THE AREA OF THE CAR AND OPENED THE VALVE CONTROL BOX. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE 1/4" PIPE LEADING FROM THE TANK TO THE "LIQUID SAMPLE VALVE" HAD COME LOOSE FROM THE PIPE NIPPLE ON THE INLET SIDE OF THE VALVE. AN ATTEMPT WAS MADE TO STOP THE LEAK USING A "FREEZE PATCH". THE FLOW OF LIQUID ETHYLENE WAS REDUCED, BUT NOT STOPPED USING THIS METHOD. A SECOND ENTRY WAS MADE TO SECURE THE LEAK. ON THE SECOND ENTRY A "PIPE SHUT-OFF CLAMP" WAS APPLIED TO THE LEAKING LINE. THIS CLAMP EFFECTIVELY SHUT OFF THE FLOW OF LIQUID FROM THE PIPE. AFTER INSPECTING THE CAR, THE CAR WAS MOVED INTO THE YARD AND ONTO A REPAIR TRACK. AN EMPTY TANK CAR WAS BROUGHT TO THE YARD AND THE CONTENTS OF APHX 2014 WERE TRANSFERRED INTO APHX 2010. THE RESIDUAL VAPORS IN APHX 2014 WERE FLARED OFF AND THE CAR WAS SECURED FOR MOVEMENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER. FRA EXEMPTION #0307170

GAGLIA NOTIFY PACIFIC WEST, CONTRACTOR, TO RESPOND AND INSPECT THE CONTAINER. MR. SLOANE STATED THE CONTRACTOR WAS NOTIFIED TO RESPOND AT MR. GAGLIA'S REQUEST. PAC WEST REPORTED LESS THAN ONE GALLON OF ALCOHOL WAS RELEASED. RELEASE WAS APPARENTLY CAUSED BY PAILS RUBBING TOGETHER.
column172: Pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: JASON, MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS, REPORTED A LEAKING TANKCAR LOCATED IN THE CENTENNIAL YARD AT 5701 VICKORY, TRACK 205, APPROXIMATELY TWENTY CARS EAST OF THE MOPAC BRIDGE. JASON STATED A CLOUD WAS HOVERING AROUND THE TANKCAR. MIKE KELLY, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. AT 03:50 AM, MGR. KELLY REQUESTED RMCC MAKE NOTIFICATION TO CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER. STATE AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE ALSO MADE. KELLY ADVISED THAT HE FOUND A VALVE LABELED V3 OPEN ALLOWING VAPORS TO BE RELEASED OUT OF THE BOX ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE CAR. KELLY CLOSED THE VALVE APPROXIMATELY ONE QUARTER TURN AND THE LEAK WAS SECURED. THE TANKCAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

column42: ETHYL METHYL KETONE OR METHYL ETHYL KETONE
column168: DOUG, CLERK, REPORTED CONTAINER EMPU 294235 ON FLATCAR BNSB 230002, LEAKED AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF PRODUCT ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE FLATCAR AND WAS LOCATED ON TRACK 1 IN THE BROOKLYN YARD. DOUG FURTHER STATED NO PERSONNEL WERE INJURED AND NO WATER WAYS WERE AFFECTED. ED WILLIAMS, ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER, WAS NOTIFIED AND STATED RMCAT, CONTRACTOR, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. AT 03:30 PM, MR. WILLIAMS REPORTED JEFF MILTONBURGER, RM CAT, CONTRACTOR, ADVISED THE CONTAINER WAS OPENED AND PERSONNEL DISCOVERED COMMODITY PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED. HOWEVER, THEY FOUND ONE FIVE GALLON CONTAINER HAD BEEN PUNCTURED. SMALL DRIPS WERE QUICKLY CONTAINED BY RM CAT PERSONNEL. THE CONTAINERS WAS PLACED INTO A LARGER PLASTIC CONTAINER AND SECURED THE PRODUCT. NO PRODUCT REACHED THE GROUND AND ALL ATTEMPTS TO NOTIFY SHIPPER, HUB CITY, WERE UNSUCCESSFUL. MR. WILLIAMS REQUESTED NOTIFICATION TO CHEMTREC, FOR SHIPPER NOTIFICATION. RON, CHEMTREC, WAS NOTIFIED AND ADVISED HE WOULD ATTEMPT NOTIFICATION OF THE SHIPPER AS WELL. AT 04:15 PM, RON MILLER, CHEMTREC, REPORTED EXTREME DIFFICULTY IN CONTACTING SHIPPER HUB CITY AND STATED HE HAS TRIED ALL PUBLIC SERVICE NUMBERS ON THE WAYBILL INFORMATION AND TWO OF THE NUMBERS ARE NOT WORKING NUMBERS, ONE WAS A RESIDENTIAL NUMBER AND IN ERROR. AT 7 PM THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THE SPILL HAD BEEN CLEANED UP AND THE CONTAINER WAS RELEASED FOR SHIPMENT.
column172: Pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column42: PHOSPHORUS, WHITE OR YELLOW DRY OR UNDER WATER OR IN SOLUTION
column168: JACKIE, NORTH PLATTE FIRE DEPARTMENT, REPORTED AN ENGINE COMPANY ON SCENE, ADDITIONAL UNITS RESPONDING, AT BAILEY YARD, IN THE EAST END OF THE YARD, ADVISING A PHOSPHORUS TANKCAR ON FIRE IN THE YARD, SMOKE SHOWING. THE TANKCAR IS LOCATED SIXTY CARS FROM THE EAST END OF THE TRAIN. FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL ISOLATED THE TANKCAR ONE HALF MILE IN EACH DIRECTION. NORTH PLATTE YARDMASTER WAS CONTACTED FOR INFORMATION AND HE STATED TANKCAR MSPX 13003 WAS ENTRAINED IN TRAIN MNPEW 20, WHICH WAS LOCATED EAST DEPARTURE FIVE, YARD TWO, TRACK 305, AND THE 64TH CAR FROM THE EAST END OF A TOTAL 111 CARS. WINDS ARE OUT OF THE SOUTH AT TEN MILES PER HOUR AND THE YARDMASTER STATED HE REMOVED YARD PERSONNEL FROM THE AFFECTED ISOLATED AREAS IN ALL DIRECTIONS FROM THE TANKCAR. STATE NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE. LANE SEKAVEC, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, WAS NOTIFIED AND HE REQUESTED KIM KEELING, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, BE NOTIFIED TO RESPOND. MGR. KEELING WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED FOR SHIPPER NOTIFICATION. AT 8:05 PM, MGR. KEELING ADVISED HE WAS ON SCENE AT THIS TIME WORKING HIS WAY CLOSER TO THE TANKCAR TO INVESTIGATE FURTHER. THERE APPEARED TO BE A VAPOR LEAK FROM THE TOP OF THE TANKCAR AND IT BORE EVIDENCE OF A PREVIOUS FIRE AND AN EARLIER RELEASE OF PRODUCT. THE TANKCAR WAS NOT ON FIRE NOW. DEAN WELLING, MONSANTO, SODA SPRINGS, ADVISED THAT A HAZMAT TEAM WAS ASSEMBLED AND READY TO RESPOND TO NORTH PLATTE YARD IF NECESSARY AND REQUESTED, TO MAKE REPAIRS TO THE TANKCAR. MGR. KEELING WAS ABLE TO TIGHTEN THE BOLTS OF THE MANWAY AND BAD ORDERED THE CAR. KIM WAS CONFERRED WITH DEAN WELLING, MONSANTO, SODA SPRINGS, AND ADVISED DEAN THAT THIS WAS AN OLDER STYLE TANKCAR. THE MANWAY GASKET WAS BLOWN OUT AND HE ADVISED HE CROSS TIGHTENED THE BOLTS, A GASKET ON ONE SIDE, BELIEVED TO BE A BAD ORDER, WAS ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE THE TANKCAR. DEAN ADVISED THE HAZMAT TEAM WOULD RESPOND TO NORTH PLATTE YARD. ON 07/21/03 AT 11:30 AM, KIM KEELING, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, REPORTED FIFTEEN POUNDS OF PRESSURE OF A NITROGEN BLANKET, WAS PLACED ON TANKCAR MSPX 13003. MR. KEELING STATED THE TANKCAR WAS RELEASED AS OF 11:30 AM.

JAY EVERETT, DIRECTOR OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS, REPORTED VAPOR RELEASED FROM THE MANWAY COVER ON TANKCAR PPGX 2862 DURING MOVEMENT AND THE TANKCAR WAS STATIONARY AND ISOLATED AT THE WEST END OF BEAUMONT YARD. MR. EVERETT FURTHER STATED NO PERSONNEL WERE INJURED. GEOFF REEDER, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. AT 12:30 PM, MGR. REEDER, REPORTED AN OUT OF PLACE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS REALIGNED. LIQUID HAD BEEN RELEASED AS A FINE MIST, COVERING THE B END OF THE CAR. VINEGAR WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE RESIDUE ON THE CAR. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: AT 0708HRS ON 7-20-03, CCTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT SAL PEREZ, MANAGER MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE HAD REPORTED TANK CAR UTLX 650132 TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. CAR WAS LOCATED ON TRACK 505, ENGLEWOOD YARD, 1-SPOT, WITH NO DRAINS OR WATERWAYS THREATENED. SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. ON ARRIVAL, MGR LERCH NOTED PRODUCT DRIPPING AT A RATE OF APPROXIMATELY 16 OUNCES AN HOUR FROM THE FLANGE OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET SPRING OPERATED PLUG TYPE VALVE, AND APPLIED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO THE SPILL SITE. MGR LERCH THEN PLACED A BUCKET TO CONTAIN DRIPPING PRODUCT AND ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THREE OF THE VALVE FLANGE BOLTS APPROXIMATELY ONE TURN EACH. AFTER FAILING TO STOP THE LEAK, MGR LERCH HAD THE CAR ISOLATED FOR FURTHER HANDLING WHICH WAS TO BE DETERMINED BY THE SHIPPER. AT APPROXIMATELY 0830HRS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE SHIPPER, B.P. EXPLORATION, AND SPOKE TO BRAD BYCZYNSKI, DIRECTOR OF CRISIS MANAGEMENT. UPON ADVISING MR. BYCZYNSKI THAT THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE HAD FAILED, HE MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO CONTACT HULCHER ENVIRONMENTAL TO CONDUCT THE TRANSFER AND REMEDIATE ANY SPILLED MATERIAL. ON 7-21-03, EMPTY TANK CAR AMCX 75922 WAS SPOTTED ADJACENT TO CAR UTLX 650132. AT 1700HRS, TRANSFER EFFORT BEGAN UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF REGIONAL CTS MANAGER TIM O'BRIEN AND WERE COMPLETED AT 2300HRS. AN FRA MOVEMENT AUTHORITY WAS SUBMITTED BY THE SHIPPER TO MOVE CAR UTLX 650132 TO HOME SHOP FOR REPAIRS. CAR AMCX 75922 WAS BILLED TO THE CONSIGNEE, AND RELEASED FOR SHIPMENT.

FABIAN, BP FACILITY (BRITISH PETROLEUM) SECURITY, REPORTED UP DELIVERED A TANKCAR TO THE BP RAIL YARD EARLIER IN THE DAY, AND IT IS NOW LEAKING. FABIAN DID NOT HAVE A TANK CAR NUMBER BUT REPORTED IT WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP. FABIAN REQUESTED A UP HAZMAT REPRESENTATIVE RESPOND TO INSPECT THE TANKCAR. FABIAN ALSO ADVISED THE LOS ANGELES COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT TEAM AND BP FIRE & HAZMAT WERE ON SCENE. THE BP FACILITY IS LOCATED AT THE INTERSECTION ALAMEDA AND SEPULVEDA BLVD. MARVIN SCOTT, BP MANAGER, REPORTED THE TANKCAR TO BE GATX 882321. DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED THE BP FIRE & HAZMAT WHILE ENROUTE AND DEVELOPED THE LOS ANGELES COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT TEAM MOUNTED THE TANKCAR AND SECURED A CLOSURE, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. AT THIS TIME NO ADDITIONAL INFORMATION WAS KNOWN, HOWEVER, IT IS BELIEVED ONLY ONE TO TWO GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST TO THE GROUND. UPON ARRIVAL, COOPER CONFERRED WITH BP COMMAND AND FIRE PERSONNEL ON SITE. THE LA COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD DEPARTED THE SCENE, HOWEVER, LA COUNTY HEALTH HAZMAT REMAINED ON THE SCENE TO OVER SEE THE CLEANUP. BP FIRE CHIEF THOMAS HENNING STATED PLANT PERSONNEL WERE INSPECTING THE CUT OF RAIL CARS IN THE PLANT YARD WHEN THEY OBSERVED A SMALL TRICKLE OF PRODUCT ON THE SIDE OF THE TANK CAR. ONCE ALL FIRE PERSONNEL WERE SET UP, THEY APPROACHED THE TANK CAR. UPON OPENING THE PROTECTIVE COVER FOR THE LIQUID AND AIR VALVES, PRODUCT WAS NOTED WEEPING FROM THE BASE OF THE BALL VALVE WHERE IT ATTACHES TO THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE. THE BALL VALVE ASSEMBLY WAS TIGHTENED THREE FULL TURNS TO SECURE THE LEAK. IT APPEARS THE PRODUCT WARMED, WHICH INCREASED THE INTERNAL PRESSURE OF THE TANK CAR, PUSHING PRODUCT UP THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE, AND OUT THE LOOSE BALL VALVE ASSEMBLY. BP HAD ECOLOGY CONTROL, THEIR HAZMAT CONTRACTOR, CLEANED THE RESIDUE FROM THE EXTERIOR OF THE RAIL CAR, PER THE DIRECTION OF THE LA COUNTY HEALTH HAZMAT OFFICER. THE GROUND AREA UNDER THE TANK CAR HAD A FEW DROPS OF PRODUCT CONCENTRATED ON THE RAILROAD TIE, WHICH WAS WIPED DOWN. THE TRACK BALLEST WAS MOVED TO INSPECT THE SURFACE DIRT, WHICH WAS FOUND TO BE CLEAR OF ANY PRODUCT. MYO JASON MALDER STATED THE TANK CAR HAD BEEN SET TO TH BP PLANT IN ERROR, AND MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO MOVE THE CAR TO VENTURA LESBRO, THE CORRECT DESTINATION.

DURING RANDOM TANKCAR INSPECTIONS, LANE SEKAVEC, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, DISCOVERED TANKCAR ACFX 200362 HAD A DEFECTIVE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE. THIS ALLOWED THE RELEASE OF VAPORS FROM THE TANKCAR. MR. SEKAVEC ALSO DISCOVERED A DEFECTIVE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP GASKET ON THE SAME CAR. THIS HAD NOT RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT. MR. SEKAVEC NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER TO ARRANGE FOR REPAIRS TO THE CAR. AFTER OBTAINING APPROVAL, MR. SEKAVEC REPLACED THE DEFECTIVE VALVE WITH A PIPE PLUG. A ONE-TIME MOVEMENT APPROVAL WAS OBTAINED SO THAT THE CAR COULD BE MOVED ON TO DESTINATION.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: JERMAINE JOHNSON, MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED TANKCAR TCXI 16001 WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANKCAR IN THE EL CENTRO YARD. MR. JOHNSON REPORTED A BRAKEMAN WAS SPLASHED IN THE FACE WITH PRODUCT AND TRANSPORTED TO EL CENTRO REGIONAL MEDICAL CENTER VIA AMBULANCE. EL CENTRO FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND ENROUTE. DENNIS JOHNSON, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED, MR. JOHNSON NOTIFIED ROBERT BAVIER, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, AND HE RESPONDED. AT 1:54 PM, DR. J MORAN, CENTER FOR TOXICOLOGY AND ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH, WAS NOTIFIED AND ADVISED HE HAD SPOKE WITH DR. JOHNSON, TREATING PHYSICIAN AT EL CENTRO REGIONAL MEDICAL CENTER'S EMERGENCY ROOM. DR. JOHNSON CAN BE REACHED AT 760-339-7254. DR. J. MORAN REPORTED THE INJURED BRAKEMAN WENT THROUGH FIFTEEN TO TWENTY MINUTES OF WASHING (EYES AND FACE). ONE DROP OF THE PRODUCT DROPPED ON THE FOREHEAD OF THE BRAKEMAN. THERE WAS NO CONTACT TO THE EYES AND THERE WAS NO INHALATION OF PRODUCT. INSPECTION OF TANKCAR DETERMINED THAT THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND THE MANWAY GASKET WAS MISALIGNED. THE TANK  CAR WAS PROPERLY SECURED AND RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

MICHAEL GUIRDRY, MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED AN EMPTY VENTING TANKCAR IDENTIFIED AS ACFX 18614, LOCATED IN THE LIVONIA YARD, TRACK 105, SPOT NUMBER ONE. MR. GUIRDRY STATED THERE WAS A SMELL OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA IN THE AIR AND REQUESTED A CHEMICAL AGENT RESPOND. FRANK LERCH, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION AND SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND REQUESTED GEOFFREY REEDER, ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION BE NOTIFIED AND RESPOND. REEDER DID NOT NOTICE ANY ODOR OF AMMONIA AROUND THE CAR. UPON OPENING THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER HE DID NOTICE AN ODOR OF AMMONIA. NO RELEASE WAS SEEN OR HEARD. ALL VALVES WERE CLOSED AND PLUGS IN TIGHT. PRESSURE ON THE CAR WAS 12 PSI. THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS TRACED TO THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. REEDER DID NOT HAVE REPLACEMENT "O" RINGS. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND ASKED TO REPLACE THE "O" RINGS. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED. THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR NORMAL MOVEMENT.

GEOFFREY REEDER, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION, REPORTED TANKCAR IAPX 1014 WAS LEAKING ARGON IN THE LIVONIA YARD. MR. REEDER REPORTED THERE WERE A CONSIDERABLE AMOUNT OF VAPORS AND LIQUID BEING RELEASED. REEDER OPENED THE CABINET ON THE SIDE OF THE CAR AND OBSERVED MOST OF THE VALVES AND FITTING COMPLETELY COVERED WITH THICK ICE. A SPRAY OF LIQUID WAS COMING OUT OF THE STEM OF THE BOTTOM FILL VALVE. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED THROUGH CHEMTREC. THE SHIPPER STATED THEY HAD A SERVICE PERSON NEARBY AND THEY WOULD RESPOND TO REPAIR THE CAR. KEITH MORSH RESPONDED AND TIGHTENED THE PACKING GLAND NUTS TO STOP THE RELEASE. THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR NORMAL TRANSPORTATION.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: DAVID WILDERMUTH, CAR FOREMAN, REPORTED TANKCAR GATX 081048 WAS LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT AT TUCSON YARD, WEST END OF TRACK SEVEN, IN THE MIDDLE OF THE YARD. DAVID ADVISED THE TANKCAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE SMALLER DOME AT THE TOP OF THE TANKCAR, WITH PRODUCT OBSERVED RUNNING DOWN THE SIDES OF THE TANK AND DRIPPING ONTO THE BALLEST AND TIES. THE TANKCAR WAS ISOLATED IN THE YARD. ROBERT BAVIER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, WAS NOTIFIED. MR. BAVIER REQUESTED RMCC MAKE STATE AND CHEMTREC NOTIFICATIONS. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS PROVIDED A COURTESY NOTIFICATION. MR. BAVIER CONTRACTED WITH ERI, CONTRACTOR, TO RESPOND AND HANDLE CLEAN UP. AT 07:13 PM, MGR. BAVIER REPORTED THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE WAS NOT SECURED TO THE TANKCAR, TWO BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND TWO BOLTS WERE MISSING. THE LINE WAS RESECURED TO THE TANKCAR AND IT WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

AT 0820HRS ON 7-30-03, CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THE FOLLOWING. DON KENGREY, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS, WEST LAKE, LA REPORTED THE LOCAL TRAIN CREW HAD OBSERVED A VAPOR RELEASE FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR GATX 61059. CREW IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED THE CAR IN YARD 4, TRACK 441 IN THE ROSE BLUFF YARD; WEST LAKE, LA FOR FURTHER HANDLING. UPON BEING NOTIFIED, CTS MGR REQUESTED THE RMCC CONTACT THE SHIPPER VIA CHEMTREC. WHILE ENROUTE, MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY ALLEN HAYES, ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGER FOR TETRA TECHNOLOGIES AND ADVISED HIM OF THE REPORTED RELEASE. MR HAYES INDICATED THAT HE WAS ENROUTE FROM HOUSTON, TX., AND THAT LOCA PLANT PERSONNEL IN WEST LAKE HAD BEEN NOTIFIED AND WERE ENROUTE TO THE CAR LOCATION. ON ARRIVAL, MGR LERCH WAS MET BY LOUISIANA STATE TROOPER SEAN LA FLEUR, LOUISIANA DEPT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY EMERGENCY RESPONDER BRANDON SIMON, BRIAN WALKER TETRA CHEMICAL FACILITY MANAGER AND ALLEN HAYES, ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGER, TETRA CHEMICAL. THERE WERE NO VISIBLE SIGNS OF RELEASE FROM THE GROUND.  HOWEVER, FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED A SLIGHT HISSING SOUND FROM THE QUICK FILL HOLE COVER, WHICH RESULTED IN FINDING FOUR OF FOUR MANWAY SWING BOLTS TO THE QUICK FILL HOLE IN PLACE NOT COMPLETELY WRENCH TIGHT. EACH BOLT WAS TIGHTENED APPROXIMATELY ONE TURN EACH, WHICH STOPPED THE RELEASE OF VAPOR. FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE CAR REVEALED FOUR BOLTS TO THE AIR LINE BLIND FLANGE LOCATED ON THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY TO BE IN POSITION, NOT COMPLETELY WRENCH TIGHT. THREE BOLTS ON THE LIQUID LINE BLIND FLANGE IN POSITION, NOT COMPLETELY WRENCH TIGHT. ALL FITTINGS WERE TIGHTENED WHICH SECURED THE CAR FOR TRANSPORTATION. IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT THERE WERE NO SIGNS OF LEAKAGE FROM THE AIR AND LIQUID LINE BLIND FLANGES. AFTER PROPERLY SECURING THE CAR, IT WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. THERE WERE NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS, OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.

STEVE AUGUSTINE, TRAIN MASTER, REPORTED TANKCAR NATX 29111 WAS LEAKING. THE TANKCAR WAS ISOLATED AT THE WEST END OF THE ALTON SOUTHERN RAILWAY YARD ON TRACK 002. MR. AUGUSTINE STATED THERE WERE NO WATER WAYS EFFECTED OR EMPLOYEE EXPOSURES. JOHN MILLER, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. RMCC MADE NOTIFICATION TO CHEMTREC. AT 01:40 PM, MGR. MILLER INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND A BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE THAT WAS NOT SEALING OFF COMPLETELY. MR MILLER STATED HE CLOSED THE VALVE, TURNED OVER THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP GASKET AND SEALED THE CAP THREADS BEFORE RELEASING THE CAR. MR. MILLER MADE CONTACT WITH DARRIN SMITH, SHIPPER (AVENTINE), AND ADVISED THE TANKCAR NEEDED TO BE SHOPPED FOR REPAIRS BEFORE BEING RELOADED.

column168: AN UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK WAS OVERFILLED DURING A TANK TRUCK DELIVERY AND PRODUCT WAS RELEASED THROUGH A DEFECTIVE GAUGE CAP ON THE UNDERGROUND TANK. THIS RELEASE WAS DISCOVERED 7-28-03.

TOTE WAS OVER FILLED.  IT CAME OUT OF THE OVERFLOW RELIEF VALVE.  CALLED CHEMTREC REPORT#07222003074.  TALKED TO LAURA WHO WILL NOTIFY ERTS.  USED ABSORBENT TO ABSORB IT THEN WIPED IT OFF WITH RAGS (USED PROTECTIVE GLOVES).

column168: DRUM SLID OFF DRUM JACKS, PUNCHING HOLE IN SIDE OF DRUM.
TED USED CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET, USED ALL PROPER PPE, AND DISPOSED OF ACCORDING TO ALL UPS PROCEDURES.

NRC REPORT #651904: SOUTHBOUND TRAIN #121 WAS IN THE PROCESS OF STOPPING AS THE DETECTOR AT MP-93 WAS GIVING A HOT BEARING INDICATION. THE TRAIN WAS BEING DIVERTED ONTO THE PASSING TRACK WHEN THE DERAILMENT OCCURRED. A WRONG BEARING ON BOXCAR GBRX322151 DERAILED ALONG WITH 8 CARS FOLLOWING IT, THREE WERE LOADED SODIUM HYDROXIDE TANK CARS AND FIVE WERE EMPTY CEMENT HOPPER CARS. NO SPILLAGE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS OCCURRED AS A RESULT OF THE DERAILMENT. WHEN TANK CAR GATX 46543 WAS BEING CLEARED FROM THE MAINLINE, A SMALL LEAK WAS NOTED NEAR THE VALVE STEM SEAL ON TOP OF THE CAR. LESS THAN 1 GALLON OF PRODUCT WAS LOST.

column42: AMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S. OR POLYAMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S.
column168: DSR DAVID INMAN IN FORMED ME THAT THE BOX THAT THE FREIGHT CAME IN ON WAS LEAKING. WE ASKED THE DSR JUAN SANCHEZ IF THE BOX WAS WET WHEN HE UNLOADED AND HE SAID THAT HE NEVER NOTICED IT THE BOX WAS LEAKING OR NOT.
WHEN THE TRAILER WAS LOADED AT CON-WAY IN BIRMINGHAM, ANOTHER FREIGHT SHIPMENT WAS PUSHED INTO ONE OF THE PAILS, CAUSING IT TO LEAK AROUND THE TOP WHERE THE LID IS SECURED TO THE PAIL.

column168: MIKE PIMENTAL WAS UNLOADING A SKID FROM THE TRAILER. ON THE SKID MIKE WAS UNLOADING WAS A SMALL PACKAGE SITTING NEXT TO THE FREIGHT THAT WAS SUPPOSED TO BE ON THE SKID NO OTHER PACKAGES WERE FOUND OTHER THAN THE SINGLE BOX

column168: DSR MORRISON FROM XLU DID NOT DUNNAGE DRUM PRO362319974 DSR C DANIELS FROM XLU LOADED 9 SKIDS BEHIND DRUM PUNCTURED DRUM

MARK REIMERS, REGIONAL MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED BY THE IMRL INTERMODAL YARD IN COUNCIL BLUFFS OF A LEAKING CONTAINER THAT ARRIVED IN THE YARD ON FRIDAY, 07-25-03.  INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT ONE FIVE GALLON PAIL LEAKED AS A RESULT OF A LOAD SHIFT DUE TO IMPROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ON A FLATCAR AND IN THE CONTAINER, WITH NO PRODUCT REACHING THE GROUND.  THE CONTAINER WAS TRANSLOADED BY AN AMERICAN PRESIDENTS LINE CONTRACTOR AND THE SPILLED MATERIAL CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.
column172: Pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: RICK SLOANE, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION AND SAFETY, REPORTED THAT WHILE ATTENDING TO ANOTHER INCIDENT, YARD PERSONNEL CONTACTED HIM REGARDING RAILCAR ACFX 17595, A LOAD OF BUTANE, THAT WAS RELEASING PRODUCT.  MR. SLOANE ADVISED THAT UPON INSPECTION A SMALL QUANTITY OF PRODUCT WAS BEING RELEASED FROM THE SAFETY VALVE, THE EXACT NATURE OF THE DEFECT WAS UNKNOWN. MR. SLOANE REQUESTED THE SHIPPER BE NOTIFIED, VIA CHEMTREC, AND CONFERRED WITH HIS CELL PHONE.  AT 11:25 PM, MGR. SLOANE WAS CONFERRED WITH THE SHIPPER WHO ADVISED PERSONNEL WOULD RESPOND IN  THE MORNING TO INSPECT AND REPAIR THE RAILCAR.  MR. SLOANE DISCUSSED THE RAILCAR WITH YARD PERSONNEL AND ADVISED THEM THAT THE RAILCAR WOULD BE SECURE UNTIL MORNING, AND TO CONTACT HIM IF ANYTHING HAPPENED.  ON 7/28 MR. SLOANE ADVISED THE CAR WAS OVERLOADED AND WAS REDUCED IN VOLUME BY TANKCAR TO TRUCK TRANSFER.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.  OVERLOAD INFORMATION WAS PROVIDED TO KEN HOLGARD OF THE FRA.

KERRY BOLEN, MANAGER OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS, REPORTED TANKCAR UTLX 645044 WAS LEAKING MOLTEN PHENOL FROM THE DOME OF THE TANKCAR.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE.  MR. BOLEN ADVISED THE TANKCAR WAS LOCATED AT YARD 1, TRACK 502, RICK SLOANE, MANGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  AT 11:05 PM, MGR. SLOANE ADVISED THE TANKCAR HAD BEEN LEAKING FROM THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE VALVE, DUE TO THE VALVE NOT BEING TIGHT ON THE THREADED NIPPLE.  MR. SLOANE TIGHTENED THE VALVE WHICH SECURED THE RAILCAR.  THE RAILCAR WAS CLEANED AT LOCOMOTIVE SERVICE TRACK WITH SOAPY WATER AND WAS OBSERVED OVERNIGHT FOR ANY ADDITIONAL LEAKAGE.  THE TANKCAR WAS RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION THE NEXT DAY.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.
